## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws at runtime on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you have a few options:

**Option A — Platform-guard the DSA path (verify-only, keep Linux/Windows working):**
```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification not supported on macOS in .NET 11");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

**Option B — Move DSA verification to a cross-platform alternative:**
Use a third-party library (e.g., Bouncy Castle) that implements DSA in managed code, so it works everywhere including macOS.

**Option C — Re-sign with a modern algorithm:**
If you control both signing and verification, migrate to **ECDSA** or **RSA**:
```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
var sig = ecdsa.SignData(data, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

For a legacy-verification scenario where you can't re-sign, **Option B** (Bouncy Castle or similar managed DSA) is likely the best path to keep all three platforms working.
